Therefore, in order to address the above issues, we designed a robust and reversible fluorescent gel with bright structural colors and high contrast for multi-dimensional information encryption (Fig. 1
                     ). Firstly, inspired by the luminous pearl oyster, its interior consists of stacked and ordered calcium carbonate nanostructures, while its exterior consists of an organic layer containing fluorescent proteins that display dazzling fluorescence under UV irradiation (Fig. 1a) [45,46]. Subsequently, we developed a composite material composed of hollow SiO2 and GQDs. The interstitial spaces of the hollow SiO2 PCs were filled with a mixture of polymer pregel containing GQDs, resulting in a stable composite containing the GQDs and PC framework, which was suitable for use in regulation synergistic effect of structural color and fluorescence (Fig. S1). Among them, GQDs were incorporated as UV-excitable fluorescent units into poly(ethylene glycol) diacrylate (PEGDA) and ethylene glycol polyacrylate (ETPTA) to prepare GQDs hydrogel (Fig. 1b). Since GQDs were fixed in the gel network through the molecular dipole-dipole interaction, we modulated different fluorescence effect by changing the maximum wavelength (λ
                     max) of the structural color (Fig. 1c). Subsequently, we adjusted the relative size of the core-shell structure of PCs to regulate the properties of wide FWHM, thereby widening the PBG. Here, the wide FWHM of fluorescence spectra could also be achieved by mixing QDs of various sizes. The properties of composite materials with wide structural color FWHM and wide fluorescent FWHM would be well applied in advanced anti-counterfeiting information encryption, thereby improving the reliability of anti-counterfeiting encryption. Moreover, the multi-level authentication of structural color and fluorescence encoding combined the concepts of hue, position, and patterns, such as "smiling faces," providing significant opportunities for anti-counterfeiting applications. By using colors to encode information in a number matrix, the encoding of fluorescence intensity was more covert (Fig. 1d). Finally, by defining and compiling the recognition process of numerical matrices, the security of the encryption process could be effectively improved, leading to a fast and convenient information decoding process.

Based on Formulas (1) and (2), PEGDA-ETPTA (n = 1.45) filled the voids within the PC, replacing the air (n = 1), resulting in an increase in effective refractive index (n

                           eff
                        ) and consequently a red-shift of the reflection peak. As the Δn increased, the reflection intensity also increased.
